<subSubSection id="44FFB0EAFFA6FFBA158BFCC2B796FBE1" pageId="13" pageNumber="238" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="0C5AE361FFA6FFBA158BFCC2B796FBE1" blockId="13.[151,1437,151,1077]" pageId="13" pageNumber="238">
<emphasis id="3E913F73FFA6FFBA158BFCC2B703FC89" bold="true" box="[199,308,835,861]" pageId="13" pageNumber="238">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species was described from an unknown number of female specimens (
<typeStatus id="D35E5DC3FFA6FFBA11FAFCC2B325FC89" box="[1206,1298,835,861]" pageId="13" pageNumber="238">syntype</typeStatus>
(s)) with the following data: “Indes nord” in “coll. Signoret”. The extant type was examined by 
<bibRefCitation id="68749E90FFA6FFBA1103FCE6B35CFC55" author="Zhang, Y. L. &amp; Webb, M. D." box="[1103,1387,870,897]" pageId="13" pageNumber="238" pagination="1 - 103" refId="ref11914" refString="Zhang, Y. L. &amp; Webb, M. D. (1996) A revised classification of the Asian and Pacific Selenocephalinae leafhoppers (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, Entomology Series, 65, 1 - 103." type="journal article" year="1996">Zhang &amp; Webb 1996: 25</bibRefCitation>
and designated as 
<typeStatus id="D35E5DC3FFA6FFBA1479FC0AB7A8FC71" box="[309,415,907,933]" pageId="13" pageNumber="238">lectotype</typeStatus>
. Male of this species can be readily recognised among species of 
<taxonomicName id="CBE598E2FFA6FFBA11C9FC0AB2CAFC71" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1870" box="[1157,1277,907,933]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Drabescus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="238" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3E913F73FFA6FFBA11C9FC0AB2CAFC71" box="[1157,1277,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="238">Drabescus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the subcontinent by the short somewhat compressed aedeagal shaft with the basal processes divergent and wider than shaft at midlength in either ventral or dorsal view and also shorter. Also, the pygofer ventral margin is serrated before the apex. The female can be recognised by the sternite VII being sinuate and neither excavated nor incised medially and nor with a median lobe.
</paragraph>
